<dl id="n51179k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n51" href="#n51179k">N51 (VI.B.44)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n51all.htm#n51179k"> 179(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> circus <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n51179k"><li>FW 560.03 </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/lexs.htm#n51179k">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/l39s.htm#n51179k">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n51179k">MS BL 47487-108</ms> </li><li>JJA 62:201 <a name="sd8" href="../../FF/fdra/sda.htm#sd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/s/sd8.htm#n51179k">Draft: III&sect;4.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>Circus</mark>. &mdash; &ldquo;To circus&rdquo; a scene is to turn it round to get it in the opposite direction to which it was set. It also applies to rostrums, or pieces of furniture if they need a change of direction. <small> William G. Fay, <a name="WGFS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WGFS"><cite title="source">A Short Glossary of Theatrical Terms</cite></a> (Aug 1930) 00</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
